conjecture(four-color): four colours suffice to colour any planar map

Francis Guthrie, colouring a map of English counties, notices that four colours
always seem to be enough. The claim: every planar map is four-colourable.

Status: math.conjectured
---
proof(kempe-chains): the two-colour Kempe-chain interchange

A maximal subgraph in two of the colours can be recoloured by swapping those two
colours along it, freeing structure elsewhere. A valid, reusable lemma.

Status: math.proved-informal
---
proof(kempe): a Kempe-chain argument four-colours every planar map

Alfred Kempe reduces to cubic maps, removes a vertex, and frees a colour by
interchanging two Kempe chains.

Status: math.proved-informal
Depends-On: kempe-chains
Closes: conjecture:four-color
---
proof(tait): reduce four-colouring to edge-three-colouring of cubic maps

Peter Guthrie Tait gives an independent argument via edge colourings of cubic
planar graphs.

Status: math.proved-informal
Closes: conjecture:four-color
---
refute(kempe)!: two Kempe chains can cross, and the interchange fails

Percy Heawood exhibits a map where the two chains Kempe recolours independently
in fact share a vertex, so the recolouring is not well defined.

Status: math.disproved
Disproves: kempe
BREAKING CHANGE: Kempe's four-colour proof is withdrawn; the conjecture is open again.
---
proof(five-color): the Kempe-chain method does prove five colours suffice

Heawood salvages the technique: for five colours a single chain interchange is
enough, and it is sound. The Five Colour Theorem stands.

Status: math.proved-informal
Depends-On: kempe-chains
---
refute(tait)!: the Petersen graph has no edge-three-colouring

Tait's reduction assumed every cubic planar bridgeless graph is edge-three-
colourable; the Petersen graph is a counterexample to the general claim.

Status: math.disproved
Disproves: tait
BREAKING CHANGE: Tait's four-colour proof is withdrawn.
---
axiomatize~(unavoidability): an unavoidable set of configurations exists

Discharging shows every planar triangulation must contain one of a fixed finite
set of configurations. The 1976 discharging search was run by computer.

Status: math.axiomatised
AXIOM: unavoidability (discharging verified by an unaudited 1976 program)
Cites: Appel & Haken 1976, Illinois J. Math.
---
axiomatize~(reducibility): each configuration in the set is reducible

No configuration in the unavoidable set can appear in a minimal counterexample.
Checked, one configuration at a time, by computer.

Status: math.axiomatised
AXIOM: reducibility (1834 configurations checked by an unaudited 1976 program)
Cites: Appel & Haken 1976, Illinois J. Math.
---
proof(appel-haken): the Four Colour Theorem, modulo the computer checks

A minimal counterexample would contain a reducible configuration, which it cannot.
The argument is sound; its trusted base is the two computer searches.

Status: math.axiomatised
Assumes: unavoidability
Assumes: reducibility
Closes: conjecture:four-color
---
proof(rsst): a smaller, cleaner proof with 633 configurations

Robertson, Sanders, Seymour, and Thomas rebuild the proof with a shorter
discharging rule and far fewer configurations. Still computer-assisted.

Status: math.axiomatised
Assumes: unavoidability
Assumes: reducibility
Supersedes: appel-haken
Closes: conjecture:four-color
---
formalize(reducibility): a kernel-checked reducibility test in Coq

Gonthier and Werner formalise the reducibility check so the kernel, not an
external program, verifies every configuration.

Formal-Statement: rocq:FourColor.reducible
Status: math.machine-checked
Axioms: none beyond Coq's
Verified-By: Coq 8.0
Proves: reducibility
---
formalize(unavoidability): a kernel-checked unavoidable set in Coq

The discharging argument is formalised, so unavoidability is checked by the
kernel as well.

Formal-Statement: rocq:FourColor.unavoidable
Status: math.machine-checked
Verified-By: Coq 8.0
Proves: unavoidability
---
formalize(four-color): a fully machine-checked Four Colour Theorem in Coq

With both lemmas kernel-checked, the whole proof has no trusted computer program
left. The theorem is machine-checked end to end.

Formal-Statement: rocq:FourColor.four_color_theorem
Status: math.machine-checked
Axioms: propositional extensionality
Verified-By: Coq 8.0
Depends-On: FourColor.reducible
Depends-On: FourColor.unavoidable
Supersedes: rsst
Closes: conjecture:four-color
